INOTIFY_INIT(2)                                                                                             Linux Programmer's Manual                                                                                             INOTIFY_INIT(2)

NNAAMMEE
       inotify_init, inotify_init1 - initialize an inotify instance

SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS
       ##iinncclluuddee <<ssyyss//iinnoottiiffyy..hh>>

       iinntt iinnoottiiffyy__iinniitt((vvooiidd));;
       iinntt iinnoottiiffyy__iinniitt11((iinntt _f_l_a_g_s));;

DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN
       For an overview of the inotify API, see iinnoottiiffyy(7).

       iinnoottiiffyy__iinniitt() initializes a new inotify instance and returns a file descriptor associated with a new inotify event queue.

       If _f_l_a_g_s is 0, then iinnoottiiffyy__iinniitt11() is the same as iinnoottiiffyy__iinniitt().  The following values can be bitwise ORed in _f_l_a_g_s to obtain different behavior:

       IINN__NNOONNBBLLOOCCKK Set the OO__NNOONNBBLLOOCCKK file status flag on the new open file description.  Using this flag saves extra calls to ffccnnttll(2) to achieve the same result.

       IINN__CCLLOOEEXXEECC  Set the close-on-exec (FFDD__CCLLOOEEXXEECC) flag on the new file descriptor.  See the description of the OO__CCLLOOEEXXEECC flag in ooppeenn(2) for reasons why this may be useful.

RREETTUURRNN VVAALLUUEE
       On success, these system calls return a new file descriptor.  On error, -1 is returned, and _e_r_r_n_o is set to indicate the error.

EERRRROORRSS
       EEIINNVVAALL (iinnoottiiffyy__iinniitt11()) An invalid value was specified in _f_l_a_g_s.

       EEMMFFIILLEE The user limit on the total number of inotify instances has been reached.

       EEMMFFIILLEE The per-process limit on the number of open file descriptors has been reached.

       EENNFFIILLEE The system-wide limit on the total number of open files has been reached.

       EENNOOMMEEMM Insufficient kernel memory is available.

VVEERRSSIIOONNSS
       iinnoottiiffyy__iinniitt() first appeared in Linux 2.6.13; library support was added to glibc in version 2.4.  iinnoottiiffyy__iinniitt11() was added in Linux 2.6.27; library support was added to glibc in version 2.9.

CCOONNFFOORRMMIINNGG TTOO
       These system calls are Linux-specific.

SSEEEE AALLSSOO
       iinnoottiiffyy__aadddd__wwaattcchh(2), iinnoottiiffyy__rrmm__wwaattcchh(2), iinnoottiiffyy(7)

CCOOLLOOPPHHOONN
       This page is part of release 4.04 of the Linux _m_a_n_-_p_a_g_e_s project.  A description of the project, information about reporting bugs, and the latest version of this page, can be found at http://www.kernel.org/doc/man-pages/.

